## DO's
*What MUST happen?*

```yaml
rules:
  - [x] Primary action (Star) must ALWAYS be one click — never buried
        When: Rendering the split-button
        Why: Star is the most frequent action and should never require two clicks

  - [x] Group dropdown items by intent with separators
        When: Building the dropdown menu
        Why: Progressive disclosure helps users scan quickly

  - [x] Show contextual badges (saved, CC, GitHub) where relevant
        When: Action has additional context
        Why: Reduces cognitive load — users know what they're clicking into

  - [x] Respect theme variants (light/dark) throughout
        When: Rendering any Quick Action element
        Why: Visual consistency with the rest of the platform

  - [x] Use optimistic updates for Star and Love
        When: User clicks star or heart
        Why: Instant feedback feels snappy — revert on API failure

  - [x] Provide auth toast for unauthenticated users
        When: User clicks an action requiring auth
        Why: Friendly prompt to sign in rather than silent failure
```

---

## DON'T's
*What must NEVER happen?*

```yaml
rules:
  - [x] Never hide the star icon — it's the primary engagement signal
        Symptom: Star button missing from a yawn card
        Risk: Users can't save or engage, breaking the signal loop

  - [x] Never require two clicks for the primary action
        Symptom: Star only available inside the dropdown
        Risk: Friction kills engagement — 2 clicks vs 1 click is 50% drop

  - [x] Never mix economic actions with reactions
        Symptom: Monetize and Love in the same visual group
        Risk: Users accidentally spend money thinking they're reacting

  - [x] Never auto-fork without user intent
        Symptom: Fork triggered by star or other action
        Risk: Unwanted repos in user's GitHub account

  - [x] Never break the sparkle animation on star
        Symptom: Star clicks but no visual feedback
        Risk: Feels broken, reduces satisfaction
```

